stories.text:
My parents were kind of poor, lower middle class; my grandparents were poor. My grandparents for their entire life, they only bought things they needed, and nothing that they merely "wanted".

I "escaped" the toxic environment where I grew up, and I loved with undiagnosed Severe Clinical Depression (and crippling Anxiety) practically my entire adult life.

Now that I am Depression-free and my Anxiety is under control, I see the world under a different lens. One things that I see is that my "problems", present and past, are/were mostly "first world problems", and that gives me perspective.

At times I remember what my grandparents used to say to me when I was a teenager, and I can just imaging what they would say about today's society's "problems".

My grandparents were a mixed of minimalism, Zen (they we devout Catholics). They were the embodiments of both "Ora et Labora" and "Chop wood, carry water".

First world problems or first world privileges? two sides of the same coin.
stories.title: Is Depression (and Anxiety Too) a First World Problem?
